  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 13:53-58",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The majority of more recent critics (Lichtenstein, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "L. J",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". p. 271 ff., de Wette, Baur, Bleek, Köstlin, Holtzmann, Keim) adhere to the view, received with special favour since Schleiermacher, that this narrative (which, moreover, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 6:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ff., comes after the raising of Jairus’ daughter) is identical with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 4:16-30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But, in that case, it becomes necessary to set aside the very precise statements in Luke’s narrative on the one hand; and, on the other, to tamper with the rigid sequence so distinctly indicated by Matthew in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 13:53-54",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 14:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as has been done in the most awkward way possible by Olshausen (“he came once more to the town in which he had been brought up”). It is not without ample reason that Storr, Paulus, Wieseler, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "chronol. Synopse",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 284 f., Ewald, have insisted that our passage is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "not",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " identical with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 4:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ff. What Luke records is an incident that took place during the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "first",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " visit of Jesus to Nazareth after the temptation in the wilderness. The only passage to which this can correspond is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 4:12-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", so that in Luke we get an explanation of what Matthew means by his ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καταλιπὼν τὴν Ναζαρέτ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". How conceivable, likewise, that on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "two",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " occasions Jesus may have been driven from Nazareth in a similar way, so that he would be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "twice",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " called upon to utter the words about the prophet being despised in his native place, “Nazarethanis priore reprehensione nihilo factis melioribus,” Beza.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 13:53-58",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Visit to Nazareth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 6:1-6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
